did.abstract: Indiana University's Office for Women's Affairs was established on August 15, 1972 in response to the growing awareness of discrimination against women in the academic community. This collection contains over forty years' worth of documents and materials from the OWA's daily operations and interactions with the Indiana University, Bloomington campus. All matters pertaining to the OWA are now handled by the Office of the Dean of Students (for student concerns) or the Provost's office (for staff and faculty concerns).

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Select files are closed to researchers. These are indicated in the finding aid. Also, the entire Complaints series is closed to researchers at this time.
Advance notice is required for access.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: The Office for Women's Affairs (OWA) was established on August 15, 1972 in response to the growing awareness of discrimination against women in the academic community. Bloomington Chancellor Byrum E. Carter stated that the OWA's purpose was to "establish a climate in which women faculty, students, and staff are provided with full opportunities for the development of their abilities."

OWA's first dean was Eva Kagan-Kans, a professor of Slavic Languages and Literature. Her function, she stated, was to be an "ombudswoman," investigating specific grievances, reviewing salaries and budgets for gender discrimination, examining access to research opportunities in graduate programs and career counseling for undergraduates at both the college and high school levels, and redressing the under representation of women at the faculty and administrative levels. She held this post from 1972 until 1975.

Jessie Lavan-Kerr, a professor of Art Education, served as OWA's second dean. In 1976, while noting the "foundational inroads" the OWA made under the leadership of Kagan-Kans, Lavan-Kerr specified a need for "redefinition" of the office, gearing it to more "action-oriented directives" regarding equal opportunities for women faculty, students, and staff. Lavan-Kerr was dean from 1975 until 1979.

OWA's third dean, D'ann Campbell, was an assistant (later associate) professor of History and an adjunct associate of Women's Studies. Campbell saw her job as an "advocate." OWA's function, she stated, lay in "coordinating, funneling, and being a catalyst for a lot of projects to enhance the status of women on campus. We're the affirmative side of Affirmative Action. We don't wait until something falls apart. We can be sensitive to areas in which there are potential problems." Under Campbell's leadership, OWA oversaw the development of such projects as creating a video dealing with sexual harassment on campus (the first of its kind in the country), addressing the lack of female social networks in graduate school, and conferences to integrate women's history into standard course work (80% of Western Civilization and American History courses never mentioned women in either books or lectures). Campbell was dean of OWA from 1979 until 1986. That year Phyllis Klotman succeeded Campbell and served until 1993 and was followed by Julia Lamber 1993-1998; Jean C. Robinson 1998-2003; Terry Dorkin 2003-2007 and Catherine Pilachowski 2007-2008. In 2008 Yvett M. Alex-Assensoh was named Dean and in 2012 following her resignation all matters pertaining to the OWA were transferred to the Office of the Dean of Students (for student concerns) or the Provost's office (for staff and faculty concerns).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into nine series: Awards and Grants, 1972-2012, undated; Publications, 1977-2012; Reports and Research, 1973-2011; Events, 1988-2009; Conferences, 1975-2007; Ongoing Programming, 1983-2012; Office Materials, 1968-2012; Audio-Visual Materials, 1990-2010; and Complaints, 1974-2010.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The Awards and Grants series (1972-2012, undated) is organized into two sub-series: Awards (1989-2010) and Grants (1972-2012, undated). The Awards sub-series is arranged alphabetically by award type and then chronologically by folder date. The Awards sub-series documents the awards offered to students, faculty, and staff, including nomination materials, award ceremony materials, and the actual awards. The Grant sub-series is arranged alphabetically by grant name and then chronologically by the folder date. The sub-series documents the OWA's relationships with grant agencies, especially the American Association of University Women (AAUW), the Department of Justice (DOJ), and the National Science Foundation (NSF).
Arranged chronologically, the publications series (1977-2012) consists of the earliest OWA newsletters, Focus and Among Women, and two copies of each volume of the OWA's Majority Report.

The Reports and Research series (1973-2011, undated), consists of three sub-series: General (1973-1981, undated), Reports and Handbooks (1986-2011), and The Status of Women at Indiana University, Bloomington (1995-2009, undated). The General sub-series and the OWA Reports and Handbooks sub-series are arranged chronologically and include research material and hardcopies of the OWA's annual reports, semester reports, office handbooks, and miscellaneous reports published by the OWA. The third sub-series, The Status of Women at Indiana University, Bloomington, documents a long-term research and publication project initiated by the OWA. The sub-series includes data collected by the Task Force on the Status of Women at IU and their related subcommittees, hardcopies of the publication, salary equity studies, correspondence, and other materials compiled throughout the project's duration.

The Events series (1988-2009, undated) is arranged chronologically and documents numerous OWA-sponsored campus events. More specifically, the OWA sponsored annual Women's History Month events, lectures and speaking engagements, and planned workshops for the women (both students and faculty) of IU Bloomington.

The Conferences series (1975-2007) is arranged chronologically and contains records pertaining to the many female-focused conferences that were both planned and attended by the OWA, especially the Women's Leadership Conference and the Women in the Workplace Conference.

The Ongoing Programming series (1983-2012, undated) consists of six, chronologically-arranged sub-series: Affirmative Action (1990-2009, undated), Commission for Public Safety (CPS) (1986-2010, undated), Mentoring Programs (1992-2012, undated), Women in Science Material (1992-2011, undated), Gender Initiatives Team (GIT) (1996-2008, undated), Family-Friendly Work Initiatives (1995-2008, undated), and Childcare Initiatives (1983-2006, undated).

The Affirmative Action sub-series (1990-2009, undated), includes correspondence, guides, and research on affirmative action at Indiana University and other Big Ten universities. Commission for Public Safety (CPS) sub-series (1986-2010, undated) includes meeting minutes, correspondence, and policy information collected throughout the OWA's participation in the campus-wide Commission, which deals primarily with safety concerns affecting all members of the IU, Bloomington campus, especially concerning pedestrian and bicycle safety, sexual assault prevention, and facilities and lighting concerns.

The Mentoring Programs sub-series is divided into three sub-sub-series: Women Faculty Mentoring Program (1996-2009), Women Partners Program (1992-2000, undated), and Mentoring General (1992-2012, undated). These sub-sub-series are arranged chronologically by the two predominant OWA mentoring programs, the Women Faculty Mentoring Program and the Women Partners Program. The third sub-sub-series consists of seven folders that pertain to OWA mentoring initiatives but do not contain material on either of the two predominant OWA mentoring programs.

The Women in Science Material sub-series (1992-2011, undated) includes material from the Women in Science Program (WISP), a program of the OWA that sought to create a supportive and proactive learning and working environment in which women in science thrive and succeed. The group was made up of dedicated science and technology faculty and developed programs that promoted female participation in science, mathematics, and technology at IU. The series additionally includes material from the Committee on Institutional Cooperation-Women in Science and Engineering (CIC-WISE) program, which is a national foundation devoted to the objectives of WISP. The OWA participated in many CIC-WISE functions and applied for CIC-WISE travel grants.

The Gender Initiatives Team (GIT) sub-series (1996-2008, undated) includes material collected by the OWA throughout their relationship with the GIT, which assists and supports students and other university members when challenged by discriminatory incidents based on race, ethnicity, nationality, religion, gender, disability, or sexual orientation.

The final two sub-series, Family-Friendly Work Initiatives (1995-2008, undated) and Childcare Initiatives (1983-2006, undated), document two important and ongoing programs initiated by the OWA, which relate to the office's primary mission to promote professional goals among women, especially those with families. The two series consist of data collected throughout studies and surveys affiliated with the programs, as well as reports, legislation, meeting minutes, advertisements, and correspondence related to the programs.

The Office Materials series (1968-2012, undated) consists of two sub-series: Meeting and Committee Minutes and Notes (1991-2012, undated) and Administrative Subject Files (1968-2012, undated). The Meeting and Committee Minutes and Notes sub-series(1991-2012, undated) is arranged chronologically and contains notes compiled during the various meetings attended by OWA employees and pertain specifically to official OWA business. The Administrative Subject files (1968-2012, undated) are arranged alphabetically by folder title and then chronologically. A large portion of the subject and reference files contain information on OWA budget, OWA policies, and the correspondence of specific OWA deans, including Jean Robinson, Terry Dworkin, and Yvette Alex-Assensoh.

The Audio-Visual Materials series (1990-2010, undated) is arranged chronologically and then alphabetically by item title or individual's last name. The series is organized by format (cassette tapes, CD-ROMs, DVDs, floppy disks, and VHS), and contains staff and event photographs, faculty interviews, recorded presentations, and office files.

The Complaints series (1974-2010) documents a large number of cases submitted, often via email, to the OWA that express concerns over tenure and promotion discrimination, sexual assault, safety concerns, etc. One of the greatest responsibilities of the OWA was to advocate on behalf of women and other IU community members who felt discriminated against. These cases are often followed-up with written reports and, therefore, there are a number of folders that contain grievance files for specific cases or specific individuals. The series is arranged chronologically and then alphabetically by folder title or the individual's last name. The entire series is restricted due to the sensitive nature of its contents.
Please contact a University Archivist with questions relating to restricted files.

separatedmaterial.head: Photographs Pulled
separatedmaterial.p: All photographs have been removed and transferred to the Indiana University Archives' photograph collection. Contact the Archives Photographs curator for access information.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: Additional records such as newsletters, annual reports, bulletins, and publications may be accessed in the Archives of Institutional Memory.

userestrict.head: Usage Restrictions
userestrict.p: Copyrights for records originating with Indiana University administrative units, departments, and other offices are held by the Trustees of Indiana University. For more information, please contact the Indiana University Archives staff.

The Indiana University Archives respects the intellectual property rights of others and does not claim any copyrights for non-university records, materials in the public domain, or materials for which we do not hold a Deed of Gift. Responsibility for the determination of the copyright status of these materials rests with those persons wishing to reuse the materials. Researchers are responsible for securing permission from copyright owners and any other rights holders for any reuse of these materials that extends beyond fair use or other statutory limitations.

Digital reproductions of archival materials from the Indiana University Archives are made available for noncommercial educational and research purposes only. If you are the copyright holder for any of the digitized materials and have questions about its inclusion on our site, please contact the Indiana University Archivist.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: [Item], Indiana University Office for Women's Affairs records, Collection C125, Indiana University Archives, Bloomington.

appraisal.head: Appraisal
appraisal.p: 44 files of mentee and mentor applications have been discarded due to the amount of sensitive information included in them. Duplicates of materials, conference registration forms, conference/event evaluations, job/program application materials, and materials with sensitive information (i.e. social security numbers) were removed from the collection.
